    <!-- Relations -->
    <h3>Relations, tuples, and attributes</h3>
    <p>A <strong>relation</strong> is a named set of tuples. Each tuple is an ordered collection of attribute values. Each attribute has a name and a domain (the set of allowed values). The <strong>schema</strong> defines the attribute names and domains. The <strong>instance</strong> is the current set of tuples.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; A relation is a set of tuples.
; Each tuple maps attribute names to values.
; We represent a relation as a list of association lists.

(define users
  (list
    (list (cons "id" 1) (cons "name" "Alice") (cons "email" "alice@db.io"))
    (list (cons "id" 2) (cons "name" "Bob")   (cons "email" "bob@db.io"))
    (list (cons "id" 3) (cons "name" "Carol") (cons "email" "carol@db.io"))))

; Get an attribute from a tuple
(define (get-attr tuple attr)
  (cdr (assoc attr tuple)))

; Display all names
(for-each
  (lambda (tuple)
    (display (get-attr tuple "name"))
    (display " ")
    (display (get-attr tuple "email"))
    (newline))
  users)
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# A relation as a list of dictionaries
users = [
    {"id": 1, "name": "Alice", "email": "alice@db.io"},
    {"id": 2, "name": "Bob",   "email": "bob@db.io"},
    {"id": 3, "name": "Carol", "email": "carol@db.io"},
]

for row in users:
    print(row['name'] + " " + row['email'])
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- Keys -->
    <h3>Keys</h3>
    <p>A <strong>superkey</strong> is any set of attributes that uniquely identifies a tuple. A <strong>candidate key</strong> is a minimal superkey (remove any attribute and it stops being unique). The <strong>primary key</strong> is the candidate key chosen to identify rows. A <strong>foreign key</strong> references the primary key of another relation, creating links between tables.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Primary key: uniquely identifies each tuple.
; Foreign key: references another relation's primary key.

(define users
  (list
    (list (cons "id" 1) (cons "name" "Alice"))
    (list (cons "id" 2) (cons "name" "Bob"))))

(define orders
  (list
    (list (cons "oid" 101) (cons "user_id" 1) (cons "item" "book"))
    (list (cons "oid" 102) (cons "user_id" 2) (cons "item" "pen"))
    (list (cons "oid" 103) (cons "user_id" 1) (cons "item" "lamp"))))

(define (get-attr tuple attr) (cdr (assoc attr tuple)))

; Look up a user by primary key
(define (find-user uid)
  (let loop ((rows users))
    (cond
      ((null? rows) #f)
      ((= (get-attr (car rows) "id") uid) (car rows))
      (else (loop (cdr rows))))))

; For each order, resolve the foreign key
(for-each
  (lambda (order)
    (let ((user (find-user (get-attr order "user_id"))))
      (display (get-attr user "name"))
      (display " ordered ")
      (display (get-attr order "item"))
      (newline)))
  orders)
`} />


    <!-- Codd's rules -->
    <h3>Codd's rules</h3>
    <p>In 1985, Codd published twelve rules (numbered 0 through 12) that a database must satisfy to be considered fully relational. The key ones: all data is represented as values in tables (Rule 1). Null values represent missing data uniformly (Rule 3). The database description is stored in the same relational structure as ordinary data (Rule 4). There is a comprehensive data sublanguage (Rule 5, fulfilled by SQL).</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Codd's Rule 1: Information Rule
; All information is represented as values in tables.
; Even metadata (table names, column names) is a table.

(define metadata
  (list
    (list (cons "table" "users")  (cons "column" "id")    (cons "type" "integer"))
    (list (cons "table" "users")  (cons "column" "name")  (cons "type" "text"))
    (list (cons "table" "users")  (cons "column" "email") (cons "type" "text"))
    (list (cons "table" "orders") (cons "column" "oid")   (cons "type" "integer"))
    (list (cons "table" "orders") (cons "column" "user_id") (cons "type" "integer"))))

(define (get-attr tuple attr) (cdr (assoc attr tuple)))

; Query the metadata: what columns does 'users' have?
(display "Columns in 'users':") (newline)
(for-each
  (lambda (row)
    (if (string=? (get-attr row "table") "users")
      (begin
        (display "  ")
        (display (get-attr row "column"))
        (display " : ")
        (display (get-attr row "type"))
        (newline))))
  metadata)
`} />


